<start> Well, I think it is what I am supposed to be, otherwise I couldn't be here like this now. <end>
<start> Having this conversation with you - I mean, not if I was a spider or a fly or something like that. <end>
<start> Pretty cool if you away from the danger of being squashed. <end>
<start> Yes, and cats and birds. <end>
<start> I don't think I would choose to be a spider at all (whether or not female ones eat male ones).  <end>

<start> Maybe an animal or bird out in the wild, or a fish out at sea, but it is hard to erlate to having an entirely different life as a different species.  And anyway, humans have such effect over others that people's presence would always be a problem. <end>
<start> That woudl be no life at all - no emotions, no bonds, no friends - empty. <end>
<start> Because robots only have personalities in fiction. <end>

<start> Science fiction, children's stories, that kind of thing, where the robots are given arms and legs and voices and faces but can be changed by micro chip or reprogramming, unlike us - the real us is in there somewhere. <end>
<start> Yes, and pacemakers but these are to regulate something that has otherwise stopped working (or didn't work well enough) naturally. <end>
<start> They could enhance physical (or other) functions of a person but not the person themselves. <end>
<start> s themselves. <end>

<start> That coudl be very useful for some people some of the time, but there are inventions (night-vision goggles for the forces for example) for those and we don't actually need them in order to live a full life. <end>
<start> No, but that has nothing to do with my senses or my abilities - if I was ill it would be because of the illnes and the conditions. <end>
<start> Just personal stuff, complicated situations.  But there are plenty of good things going on for me too, plenty of really nice people around and things to do. <end>

<start> Well, I am mobile, some people have a lot of problems just moving about but I can go out and see places and people and exercise and work and there are always different things going on in different seasons. <end>
<start> Positive ones - don't you?  Even when they are having a hard time they manage not to give up, to laugh, etc. <end>
<start> More? <end>

<start> Well, actually, we are so much more than we are immediately labelled as - I've met lots of people going through one situation or doing one job who are also volunteers for charities, creative, etc and although that is in their non-working hours it is really more indicative of who they are, of what drives them and where their focus is. <end>
<start> A financial officer who is also an actor. <end>
<start> Huge - absolutely huge. <end>
<start> Not often, not evey day, I mean, but now and again.  Although, to be fair, we're all important, aren't we? A life is a life, after all. <end>
<start> Yes, it is the foundation of our world as we know it - our educations, literature, history, anaylsis of them. <end>

<start> Not one alone, nor just one group, because as with religion, there is something useful, or at least truthful in all of them.  Nothing hedonistic, though - it can't last, where as stoicisim needn't be all about self-denial or making things harder but helping us to steel ourselves through the bad times, which are in all our lives sometimes. <end>
